      "content": "You are absolutely right to want to cut through the goblin noise and look at the hard numbers! Making extra payments toward the principal is definitely the most effective way to speed things up, and the timing matters immensely.\n\nIf you make an extra payment at the **beginning** of the loan, you are striking while the goblin's hoard is still massive. By paying down that large principal balance early, you immediately reduce the \"goblin tax\" (interest) that will be charged on the remaining months. Since interest is calculated on the balance, lowering that balance right away means the goblin has less gold to eat from your future payments. It's like cutting off the goblin's head before it can feast; you save the most interest because the compounding effect has less time to work against you.\n\nIf you wait until the **end** of the loan term to make an extra payment, the goblin has already been gnawing away at your principal for years. By then, the balance is small, so the interest rate is lower, but you have already paid a significant amount of \"goblin tax\" on the high balance during those early years. While an extra payment at the end will still reduce the total interest",
